<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="75" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="75">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="75">
Although the species originally occurred exclusively in Northern Asia from Altai to Japan (
<bibRefCitation author="Cherepanov, AI" journalOrPublisher="Oxonian Press, New Delhi" pageId="47" pageNumber="106" title="Cerambycidae of northern Asia. Vol. 2. Cerambycinae Part II." year="1990 b">Cherepanov 1990b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Danilevsky, ML" journalOrPublisher="International almanac" pageId="48" pageNumber="107" url="http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" year="2018 a">Danilevsky 2018a</bibRefCitation>
), it was recently accidentally introduced into North America (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="LaBonte, JR" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="50" pageNumber="109" pagination="554 - 564" title="Nonindigenous woodboring Coleoptera (Cerambycidae, Curculionidae: Scolytinae) new to Oregon and Washington, 1999 - 2002: Consequences of the intercontinental movement of raw wood products and solid wood packing materials." volume="107" year="2005">LaBonte et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
), where it is considered an invasive species. It was widely discussed in a previous paper concerning the longhorn beetles of Mongolia (
<bibRefCitation author="Karpinski, L" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="50" pageNumber="109" pagination="107 - 150" title="New data on the longhorn beetles of Mongolia with particular emphasis on the genus Eodorcadion Breuning, 1947 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.739.23675" volume="739" year="2018">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Karpiński">Karpinski</normalizedToken>
et al. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="75">
Several specimens were reared from birch wood 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula" order="Fagales" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Betula</taxonomicName>
sp. collected in the hilly grove (Fig. 12D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
